        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> I stand before you humiliated, and admit I was wrong.  My apologies to all of you and, especially, Velous.  I sit now at computer from home, in a completely more relaxed state of mind than earlier at work, and now see that my first impression of your post may have been wrong.</P><P>What got me was the part, "This board has had the biggest impact on me since the Navy."  I immediately associated this to something in my past, and very likely still going on, to some degree, in many people's lives.  This is losing oneself to an addiction like this game.  </P><P>If a team of psychologists were not part of the designers of EQ, the team could not have done a better job of creating something as insiduously addicting as EQ is to a certain personality type that we gamers tend to be.  </P><P>The never-ending next objective of getting that little bit extra of exp, or that next level, or that next piece of equipment is that which really gets to some of us oriented naturally in that way.  Too much attachment can lead to loss of real life experiences, problems at work or at home, and, basically, losing oneself in what, in the end, is only a game.  </P><P>Entertainment is important.  Very important.  But, sometimes entertainment turns into a serious problem, and realizing a problem exists is sometimes difficult or impossible.</P><P>Again, now that I have re-read your post in a calmer state of mind, I see that it was presumptous of me to infer any of my above association to your statements.  It is clear to me now that you may have meant something completely different.  My apologies.</P><P>I will do all of you a favor and refrain from posting from work! :-)</P><P>Game on!  but, also take a walk in a park every so often.</P><P><BR>Vaam<BR>48 DElf Necro ECI<BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=244091" target="_blank">http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=244091</a></P><P>